    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 73,
    "last_activity_date" : 1268160605,
    "creation_date" : 1268160605,
    "answer_id" : 2411660,
    "question_id" : 2411487,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>As you mentioned in a comment, you're using log4j.  I discovered (inadvertently) a place where I had written</p>\n\n<pre><code>LOG.error(exc);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>instead of the typical</p>\n\n<pre><code>LOG.error(\"Some informative message\", e);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>through laziness or perhaps just not thinking about it.  The unfortunate part of this is that it doesn't behave as you expect.  The logger API actually takes Object as the first argument, not a string - and then it calls toString() on the argument.  So instead of getting the nice pretty stack trace, it just prints out the toString - which in the case of NPE is pretty useless.</p>\n\n<p>Perhaps this is what you're experiencing?</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 57112,
      "reputation" : 38662,
      "user_id" : 171061,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 76,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/891e2f14eb568ff3e5b290fbd2fb4e05?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Steven Schlansker",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/171061/steven-schlansker"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1268165644,
    "creation_date" : 1268165644,
    "answer_id" : 2412217,
    "question_id" : 2411487,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Alternate suggestion - if you're using Eclipse, you could set a breakpoint on NullPointerException itself (in the Debug perspective, go to the \"Breakpoints\" tab and click on the little icon that has a ! in it)</p>\n\n<p>Check both the \"caught\" and \"uncaught\" options - now when you trigger the NPE, you'll immediately breakpoint and you can then step through and see how exactly it is handled and why you're not getting a stack trace.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 47283,
      "reputation" : 723399,
      "user_id" : 139985,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 69,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/147c5a9cc1feec049c50da791ac7d144?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Stephen C",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/139985/stephen-c"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1268175089,
    "last_edit_date" : 1268175089,
    "creation_date" : 1268174507,
    "answer_id" : 2413168,
    "question_id" : 2411487,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>(Your question is still unclear on whether your code is calling <code>printStackTrace()</code> or this is being done by a logging handler.)</p>\n\n<p>Here are some possible explanations about what might be happening:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>The logger / handler being used has been configured to only output the exception's message string, not a full stack trace.</p></li>\n<li><p>Your application (or some third-party library) is logging the exception using <code>LOG.error(ex);</code> rather than the 2-argument form of (for example) the log4j Logger method.</p></li>\n<li><p>The message is coming from somewhere different to where you think it is; e.g. it is actually coming some third-party library method, or some random stuff left over from earlier attempts to debug.</p></li>\n<li><p>The exception that is being logged has overloaded some methods to obscure the stacktrace.  If that is the case, the exception won't be a genuine NullPointerException, but will be some custom subtype of NPE or even some unconnected exception.  </p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>I think that the last possible explanation is pretty unlikely, but people do at least contemplate doing this kind of thing to \"prevent\" reverse engineering.  Of course it only really succeeds in making life difficult for honest developers.</p>\n"
  }, {
